If you want, I can sketch that model — I think it might click nicely with how you designed **ThesPub**.

Yes — and I think this version is the most elegant.

## The key move

Instead of:

* Shape implements requirement
* Requirement is separate resource

you say:

> **The Shape itself is the Requirement**

So a shape is not just a validator artefact. It is also a first-class requirement resource.

That gives you:

* one IRI
* one source of truth
* one object to document
* one object to validate with

## Basic pattern

A shape can be both:

* `sh:NodeShape` or `sh:PropertyShape`
* `req:Requirement`

For example:

```turtle
@prefix sh:      <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> .
@prefix skos:    <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .
@prefix req:     <https://w3id.org/requirements#> .
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix thes:    <https://example.org/def/thespub/validator#> .

thes:THES-01
    a sh:NodeShape , req:Requirement ;
    sh:targetClass skos:Concept ;
    sh:property [
        sh:path skos:prefLabel ;
        sh:minCount 1 ;
    ] ;
    dcterms:title "Concept prefLabel requirement"@en ;
    dcterms:description "Each skos:Concept must have at least one skos:prefLabel."@en .
```

That is already pretty compelling.

## Why this is strong

### 1. No duplication

You do not need:

* `thes:THES-01` as requirement
* `thes:ConceptPrefLabelShape` as shape

Those become the same thing.

### 2. Stable identifiers

Your requirement number is the shape IRI:

```turtle
thes:THES-01
```

That is lovely and clean.

### 3. Documentation becomes easier

You can generate a requirements table directly from the shapes:

* IRI
* title
* description
* target
* constraint details
* severity

### 4. Validation reports can point straight to the requirement

If a SHACL engine reports the source shape, that shape is already the requirement IRI.

No mapping layer needed.

## What metadata would the shape-requirement need?

I’d keep a small requirement annotation layer on top of SHACL.

Something like:

```turtle
@prefix sh:        <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> .
@prefix req:       <https://w3id.org/requirements#> .
@prefix dcterms:   <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix schema:    <https://schema.org/> .
@prefix thes:      <https://example.org/def/thespub/validator#> .

thes:THES-01
    a sh:NodeShape , req:Requirement ;
    dcterms:title "Concept prefLabel requirement"@en ;
    dcterms:description "Each skos:Concept must have at least one skos:prefLabel."@en ;
    schema:identifier "THES-01" ;
    sh:targetClass skos:Concept ;
    sh:property [
        sh:path skos:prefLabel ;
        sh:minCount 1 ;
        sh:severity sh:Violation ;
        sh:message "Concept must have at least one prefLabel."@en
    ] .
```

This gives you both:

* human-readable requirement text
* executable validation logic

## Where this gets really nice

You can distinguish between:

* **normative requirement text**
* **validation message**

Those are not the same thing.

For example:

```turtle
dcterms:description "Each skos:Concept must have at least one skos:prefLabel."@en ;
```

is the requirement statement.

But:

```turtle
sh:message "Add a skos:prefLabel to this Concept."@en
```

is validator guidance.

That separation solves one of the big problems you’ve been wrestling with.

## You may want one extra property

I would consider adding a dedicated property for the normative statement, instead of overloading `dcterms:description`.

Maybe:

```turtle
thes:requirementStatement
```

or more generally:

```turtle
prof:hasResourceRole`-style patterns won't quite fit
```

But honestly, `dcterms:description` is fine if you want to stay minimalist.

A slightly richer pattern could be:

```turtle
thes:THES-01
    a sh:NodeShape , req:Requirement ;
    dcterms:title "Concept prefLabel requirement"@en ;
    skos:definition "Each skos:Concept must have at least one skos:prefLabel."@en ;
```

I could imagine you liking `skos:definition` here, because it has a normative, crisp feel.

## NodeShape vs PropertyShape question

This model works for both.

Example property-shape-as-requirement:

```turtle
thes:THES-02
    a sh:PropertyShape , req:Requirement ;
    sh:path skos:prefLabel ;
    sh:minCount 1 ;
    dcterms:title "prefLabel cardinality"@en ;
    dcterms:description "A required property must occur at least once."@en .
```

But I suspect for readability and reporting, you’ll prefer **NodeShapes as requirement units**, with embedded property constraints.

That gives each requirement a nice self-contained identity.

## What about non-SHACL-expressible requirements?

This is the main limitation.

Some requirements are about:

* persistence
* governance
* publication process
* human-readable documentation
* URI policy

Those may not be expressible in core SHACL.

You have two choices:

### Option A

Allow `req:Requirement` resources that are not SHACL shapes.

So:

* some requirements are executable
* some are prose-only

### Option B

Keep SHACL-REQ only for the executable subset.

I think Option A is more robust.

That gives you a single requirements universe, where some members are also shapes.

Like this:

```turtle
thes:THES-01 a req:Requirement , sh:NodeShape .
thes:THES-02 a req:Requirement , sh:NodeShape .
thes:THES-99 a req:Requirement .
```

That is actually a very clean architecture.

## This may be the sweet spot

So the mature version of SHACL-REQ might be:

> All requirements are RDF resources.
> Some requirements are also SHACL shapes.
> When they are, the shape is the normative and executable form of the requirement.

That avoids overclaiming that SHACL can do everything, while still making SHACL central.

## Why this is better than “SHACL generates requirements”

Because it avoids a second artefact layer.

Instead of:

* shape
* generated requirement resource

you just have:

* requirement resource, optionally executable as a shape

That is simpler, more Latour-friendly really: fewer intermediaries.

## Very compact design pattern

Here’s the pattern I’d seriously consider for ThesPub:

```turtle
@prefix tpv:     <https://data.example.org/def/thespub/validator#> .
@prefix req:     <https://w3id.org/requirements#> .
@prefix sh:      <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> .
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix skos:    <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .

tpv:THES-01
    a req:Requirement , sh:NodeShape ;
    dcterms:title "Concept prefLabel requirement"@en ;
    dcterms:description "Each skos:Concept must have at least one skos:prefLabel."@en ;
    sh:targetClass skos:Concept ;
    sh:property [
        sh:path skos:prefLabel ;
        sh:minCount 1 ;
        sh:severity sh:Violation ;
        sh:message "Concept must have at least one prefLabel."@en
    ] .
```

Then your HTML spec can be generated from the validator graph.

## My recommendation

For ThesPub, I’d explore this model:

* Requirement IRIs live in the validator namespace
* Each executable requirement is both `req:Requirement` and `sh:NodeShape` or `sh:PropertyShape`
* Non-executable requirements are plain `req:Requirement`
* `dcterms:title` + `dcterms:description` carry the normative prose
* `sh:message` carries the validator-facing guidance

That gives you a very elegant SHACL-REQ story.

